Analyzing similar code for swapping positions in 2D match-3 games, the following code snippets should provide you with a good starting point.

1. Swap two game objects in 2D
To swap the positions of two game objects, you can typically create a Coroutine that will handle the smooth transition between the positions of the two objects:

```csharp
public IEnumerator Swap(GameObject firstObj, GameObject secondObj, float swapTime)
{
    float elapsedTime = 0.0f;

    Vector3 firstObjStartPos = firstObj.transform.position;
    Vector3 secondObjStartPos = secondObj.transform.position;

    while (elapsedTime < swapTime)
    {
        elapsedTime += Time.deltaTime;

        firstObj.transform.position = Vector3.Lerp(firstObjStartPos, secondObjStartPos, elapsedTime / swapTime);
        secondObj.transform.position = Vector3.Lerp(secondObjStartPos, firstObjStartPos, elapsedTime / swapTime);

        yield return null;
    }

    firstObj.transform.position = secondObjStartPos;
    secondObj.transform.position = firstObjStartPos;
}
```

You can call this Coroutine in any script by using:

