To create a Lua event that triggers a JavaScript function to toggle the UI on and off without needing an argument, you can follow these steps:

1. Modify your `script.js` file to add a new function named `toggleUI`.

```javascript
// script.js

// ...

// Toggle visibility of the UI
function toggleUI() {
    const main = document.getElementById("main");
    main.style.display = main.style.display === "none" ? "flex" : "none";
}

// ...

window.addEventListener("message", (event) => {
    // ...
    else if (event.data.type === "toggleUI") {
        toggleUI();
    }
});
```

2. Create a new Lua file (e.g., `main.lua`) to register the client-side event. This event will be received from the server to toggle the UI.

```lua
-- main.lua

RegisterNetEvent("your_event_name:toggleUI")
AddEventHandler("your_event_name:toggleUI", function()
    SendNUIMessage({ type = "toggleUI" })
end)
```

3. Create a new Lua file (e.g., `server.lua`) to trigger the event when needed. You can trigger the event from the server-side using `TriggerClientEvent()` function. This example demonstrates triggering the event when a command `/toggleUI` is entered.

```lua
-- server.lua

RegisterCommand("toggleUI", function(source, args, rawCommand)
    TriggerClientEvent("your_event_name:toggleUI", source)
end, false)
```

4. Add the following lines inside the `fxmanifest.lua` to include the newly created Lua files.

```lua
-- fxmanifest.lua

client_script "main.lua"
server_script "server.lua"
```

Now, when a player types `/toggleUI` in the game, it will trigger the `toggleUI` event, which in turn toggles the UI on and off in the `script.js` file.

