4. Access the Google Sheets API:
After successful authentication, create a Google Sheets API service:

```java
private Sheets createSheetsService(GoogleSignInAccount account) {
    HttpTransport transport = AndroidHttp.newCompatibleTransport();
    JsonFactory jsonFactory = JacksonFactory.getDefaultInstance();

    return new Sheets.Builder(transport, jsonFactory, account.getCredential())
            .setApplicationName("YourAppName")
            .build();
}
```

5. Edit the column:
To edit a column in a Google Sheet, you can utilize the "batchUpdate" method. Determine the spreadsheet ID and the range of the column you wish to edit. Here's a code snippet that updates a column:

```java
private void updateColumn(Sheets service, String spreadsheetId, String range, List<Object> valuesToUpdate) {
    List<ValueRange> dataToUpdate = new ArrayList<>();

    for (int i = 0; i < valuesToUpdate.size(); i++) {
        String cellRange = range + (i + 1); // Assuming the range starts with the first row
        ValueRange valueRange = new ValueRange().setRange(cellRange).setValues(Collections.singletonList(Collections.singletonList(valuesToUpdate.get(i))));
        dataToUpdate.add(valueRange);
    }

    BatchUpdateValuesRequest batchUpdate = new BatchUpdateValuesRequest()
            .setValueInputOption("RAW")
            .setData(dataToUpdate);

    try {

        BatchUpdateValuesResponse result = service.spreadsheets().values().batchUpdate(spreadsheetId, batchUpdate).execute();

    } catch (UserRecoverableAuthIOException authException) {
        startActivityForResult(authException.getIntent(), REQUEST_AUTHORIZATION);
    } catch (IOException e) {
        e.printStackTrace();
    }
}
```

Make sure to call this method in a background thread, such as using an `AsyncTask`. Pass the Google Sheets API service and the required parameters, and the app will edit the column in the specified Google Sheet.

To run a Python script on a Raspberry Pi 4 using Android Studio, you need to create an Android app that communicates with the Raspberry Pi via either SSH (Secure Shell) or a web server API. In this example, I'll show you how to create an Android app that communicates with the Raspberry Pi via SSH.

First, add the following dependency to your app's build.gradle to handle the SSH connection using the JSch library:

```groovy
dependencies {
    ...
    implementation 'com.jcraft:jsch:0.1.55'
}
```

Then, in your Android project, you can create a function to run the Python script through SSH:

```java
import com.jcraft.jsch.ChannelExec;
import com.jcraft.jsch.JSch;
import com.jcraft.jsch.Session;
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;

public void runPythonScriptOnRaspberryPi(
        final String user, final String password,
        final String host, final int port, 
        final String pythonScriptPath) {
    new Thread(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            try {
                JSch jsch = new JSch();
                Session session = jsch.getSession(user, host, port);
                session.setPassword(password);
                session.setConfig("StrictHostKeyChecking", "no");
                session.connect();

                String command = "python3 " + pythonScriptPath;
                ChannelExec channel = (ChannelExec) session.openChannel("exec");
                BufferedReader in = new BufferedReader(
                        new InputStreamReader(channel.getInputStream()));
                channel.setCommand(command);
                channel.connect();

                String msg;
                while ((msg = in.readLine()) != null) {
                    System.out.println(msg);
                }

                channel.disconnect();
                session.disconnect();
            } catch (Exception e) {
                e.printStackTrace();
            }
        }
    }).start();
}
```

Finally, call this function with the appropriate parameters (including your Raspberry Pi SSH credentials and Python script path):

```java
String user = "pi";  // Your SSH username, usually "pi" for Raspberry Pi
String password = "your_password";  // Your SSH password
String host = "raspberry_pi_ip_address";  // Your Raspberry Pi IP address
int port = 22;  // SSH port, usually 22
String pythonScriptPath = "/path/to/your/python_script.py";  // Your Python script path on Raspberry Pi

runPythonScriptOnRaspberryPi(user, password, host, port, pythonScriptPath);
```

Make sure to replace the placeholder values with your Raspberry Pi's SSH credentials and the path to your Python script on the Raspberry Pi.

Keep in mind that running network operations on the main thread is not recommended for Android apps. This example uses a separate thread for the SSH connection, but you should consider using an AsyncTask, ThreadPoolExecutor or Coroutine to handle network tasks more efficiently.

